Here is an example of a function in JavaScript that sets the background color of a web page to a randomly generated shade of blue, while ensuring that the generated color is not too similar to any existing colors on the web page:

```javascript
function setRandomBlueBackgroundColor() {
  // Generate random hue, saturation, and lightness values within the specified ranges
  var hue = Math.floor(Math.random() * (240 - 180 + 1)) + 180; // Random hue between 180 and 240
  var saturation = Math.floor(Math.random() * (100 - 50 + 1)) + 50; // Random saturation between 50% and 100%
  var lightness = Math.floor(Math.random() * (80 - 20 + 1)) + 20; // Random lightness between 20% and 80%

  // Convert the hue, saturation, and lightness values to a CSS color string
  var color = "hsl(" + hue + ", " + saturation + "%, " + lightness + "%)";

  // Check if the generated color is too similar to any existing colors on the web page
  var existingColors = document.querySelectorAll("*[style*='background-color']"); // Get all elements with inline background-color styles
  var colorDifferenceThreshold = 20; // Minimum difference in hue value between colors
  var saturationDifferenceThreshold = 10; // Minimum difference in saturation value between colors
  var lightnessDifferenceThreshold = 10; // Minimum difference in lightness value between colors

  for (var i = 0; i < existingColors.length; i++) {
    var existingColor = existingColors[i].style.backgroundColor;
    var existingHSL = existingColor.replace(/[^\d,]/g, "").split(","); // Extract the hue, saturation, and lightness values from the existing color

    // Calculate the differences in hue, saturation, and lightness values between the existing color and the generated color
    var hueDifference = Math.abs(hue - existingHSL[0]);
    var saturationDifference = Math.abs(saturation - existingHSL[1]);
    var lightnessDifference = Math.abs(lightness - existingHSL[2]);

    // If any of the differences are smaller than the thresholds, generate a new color and repeat the process
    if (hueDifference < colorDifferenceThreshold || saturationDifference < saturationDifferenceThreshold || lightnessDifference < lightnessDifferenceThreshold) {
      setRandomBlueBackgroundColor();
      return; // Stop execution of the function
    }
  }

  // Set the background color of the web page to the generated color
  document.body.style.backgroundColor = color;
}

// Call the function to set the initial background color
setRandomBlueBackgroundColor();
```

In this function, we first generate random values for the hue, saturation, and lightness within the specified ranges. We then convert these values to a CSS color string using the HSL (Hue, Saturation, Lightness) color model.

Next, we check if the generated color is too similar to any existing colors on the web page. We use the `querySelectorAll` method to select all elements with inline `background-color` styles and compare the hue, saturation, and lightness values of the generated color with those of the existing colors.

If any of the differences in hue, saturation, or lightness values are smaller than the specified thresholds, we recursively call the `setRandomBlueBackgroundColor` function to generate a new color and repeat the process. This ensures that we generate a color that is sufficiently different from any existing colors on the web page.

Finally, if the generated color passes the similarity check, we set the background color of the web page to the generated color using the `style.backgroundColor` property.

