import re

def convert_to_snake_case(input_string):
    # Function to convert camel case to snake case
    def camel_to_snake(name):
        name = re.sub('(.)([A-Z][a-z]+)', r'\1_\2', name)
        return re.sub('([a-z0-9])([A-Z])', r'\1_\2', name).lower()

    # Function to remove non-alphanumeric characters except underscores
    def less_breakable(name):
        return re.sub(r'\W', '', name)

    # Apply camel to snake case conversion and remove non-alphanumeric characters
    modified_string = camel_to_snake(less_breakable(input_string))
    return modified_string
```

The `convert_to_snake_case` function first applies the `less_breakable` function to remove non-alphanumeric characters except underscores from the input string. Then, it uses the `camel_to_snake` function to convert the modified string from camel case to snake case. Finally, the modified string is returned as the output.

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdbool.h>
#include <ctype.h>

// Recursive function to check if a given string is a palindrome
bool isPalindrome(char str[], int start, int end) {
    // Base case: if start and end meet or cross each other, it is a palindrome
    if (start >= end) {
        return true;
    }

    // Ignore non-alphanumeric characters and convert to lowercase
    while (!isalnum(str[start])) {
        start++;
    }
    while (!isalnum(str[end])) {
        end--;
    }
    str[start] = tolower(str[start]);
    str[end] = tolower(str[end]);

    // Check if the characters at start and end are equal
    if (str[start] != str[end]) {
        return false;
    }

    // Recursively check the remaining substring
    return isPalindrome(str, start + 1, end - 1);
}

int main() {
    char str[1000000];
    printf("Enter a string: ");
    fgets(str, sizeof(str), stdin);

    // Check if the given string is a palindrome
    if (isPalindrome(str, 0, strlen(str) - 1)) {
        printf("The string is a palindrome.\n");
    } else {
        printf("The string is not a palindrome.\n");
    }

    return 0;
}
```
This program uses a recursive function `isPalindrome` to check if a given string is a palindrome. The function takes the string, the start index, and the end index as parameters. It compares the characters at the start and end positions, ignoring any non-alphanumeric characters and considering the case of the characters. If the characters are not equal, it returns `false`. Otherwise, it recursively calls itself with the start index incremented and the end index decremented until the start and end indices meet or cross each other, indicating that the string is a palindrome. The program reads a string from the user, calls the `isPalindrome` function, and prints whether the string is a palindrome or not. The program can handle strings of length up to 10^6 characters efficiently.

